# Internationalization (i18n) Rules

## Mandatory Locales

English (`en`) and Polish (`pl`) are **mandatory**. Both must be 100% complete at all times. CI fails on any missing PL key.

## No Hardcoded Strings

Every user-facing string must go through `t('namespace:key')` from `@locus/i18n`. This includes:

- Button labels, input placeholders, tooltips
- Error messages, success messages, empty states
- Navigation labels, page titles, section headers
- Notification text, intervention messages
- Help content short descriptions

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD
<Button>{t('common:save')}</Button>
<EmptyState title={t('notes:emptyTitle')} description={t('notes:emptyDescription')} />

// ❌ BAD
<Button>Save</Button>
<EmptyState title="No notes yet" description="Create your first note" />
```

## Adding New Strings

1. Add the key to the appropriate `en/{namespace}.json` file first.
2. Immediately add the Polish translation to `pl/{namespace}.json`.
3. Use ICU MessageFormat for plurals and interpolation:

```json
// en/tasks.json
{ "activeCount": "{count, plural, one {# task} other {# tasks}}" }

// pl/tasks.json
{ "activeCount": "{count, plural, one {# zadanie} few {# zadania} many {# zadań} other {# zadań}}" }
```

## Date & Number Formatting

Use `Intl.DateTimeFormat` and `Intl.NumberFormat` with the active locale. Never hardcode date formats like `MM/DD/YYYY`.

## AI Output

When the user's locale is not English, AI prompts must include `Respond in {locale name}` to match the user's language.
